03965nam a22006615i 9780226480473DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264804737 a10.7208/97802264804732doi  a(DE-B1597)524494  a(OCoLC)1006509884  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHG501 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a332.497309032231 aSklansky, Jeffrey, eauthor.10aSovereign of the Market :bThe Money Question in Early America /cJeffrey Sklansky. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b12 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Beginnings, 1500-190000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Elusive Sovereign -- tPart One. Paper Money and the Problem of Circulation in the Colonial Era -- tPart Two. Commercial Banking and the Problem of Representation in the Jacksonian Era -- tPart Three. Big Business and the Problem of Association in the Gilded Age and Progressive Era -- tConclusion: The Magician's Glass -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat should serve as money, who should control its creation and circulation, and according to what rules? For more than two hundred years, the "money question" shaped American social thought, becoming a central subject of political debate and class conflict.  Sovereign of the Market reveals how and why this happened. Jeffrey Sklansky's wide-ranging study comprises three chronological parts devoted to major episodes in the career of the money question. First, the fight over the innovation of paper money in colonial New England. Second, the battle over the development of commercial banking in the new United States. And third, the struggle over the national banking system and the international gold standard in the late nineteenth century. Each section explores a broader problem of power that framed each conflict in successive phases of capitalist development: circulation, representation, and association. The three parts also encompass intellectual biographies of opposing reformers for each period, shedding new light on the connections between economic thought and other aspects of early American culture. The result is a fascinating, insightful, and deeply considered contribution to the history of capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aBanks and bankingzUnited States. 0aCurrency questionzUnited States. 0aMoneyzUnited States. 0aMoney--United States. 4aassociation. 4abanking. 4acapitalism. 4acirculation. 4aclass. 4acurrency. 4amarket. 4amoney question. 4amoney. 4apolitical economy. 4arepresentation. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226480473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226480473.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles